// Canonical Sutra definitions for memory / lookup operations.
//
// The runtime hashmap is a single accumulator vector built by adding
// rotation-bound (key, value) pairs together. This file provides the
// named functions; the surface syntax `dict<K, V>` (subscript assign /
// read) lowers to the same operations.
//
// The dict at runtime is ONLY the accumulator vector. There is no
// stored codebook of values; cleanup happens at the call site against
// the caller's statically-known codebook. The codebook is compile-time
// / IO state, not a runtime field of the dict.


// ==========================================================================
// Section 1 — implemented in pure Sutra
// ==========================================================================


// hashmap_new — empty accumulator (zero vector). Neutral element for
// `+` over rotation-bound pairs.
function vector hashmap_new() {
    return zero_vector();
}


// hashmap_set — store `value` at `key` by adding `bind(key, value)` to
// the accumulator. Functional: returns a new accumulator.
//
// No normalization on the bundle. Per-write normalization would corrupt
// the magnitudes the cleanup step downstream depends on; the caller
// normalizes at retrieval time if it wants.
function vector hashmap_set(vector acc, vector key, vector value) {
    return acc + bind(key, value);
}


// hashmap_get — recover the value at `key`. Returns the raw recovered
// vector — clean signal plus ~1/sqrt(N) noise from the other entries.
// Caller is responsible for cleanup (argmax_cosine against the
// statically-known codebook, MLP attractor, iterative cleanup, etc.).
//
// Capacity at d=868: ~32 keys recover cleanly, 90% accuracy at k=48
// against a 200-filler codebook. See
// planning/findings/2026-04-23-rotation-hashmap-capacity-extended-state.md.
function vector hashmap_get(vector acc, vector key) {
    return unbind(key, acc);
}


class Memory extends vector {
    static intrinsic method vector zero_vector();
}
